WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:14.000
Hi, I'm Garrett Grohlman, a professional educator at RStudio and the author of two books on R.

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:19.000
I've put together these videos to teach you some of the main ideas of doing data wrangling with R and the Tidyverse.

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:25.000
If you're not familiar with the Tidyverse, it's a collection of R packages that are designed to help you do data science.

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:32.000
In this series of short videos, we will walk through some of the most useful tools for wrangling your data with R.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:40.000
Before we dive in, I want to briefly motivate why this topic is so important and outline how these resources are organized.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:53.000
To quote an article from the New York Times, data scientists spend from 50% to 80% of their time mired in the mundane labor of collecting and preparing data before it can be explored for useful information.

00:00:53.000 --> 00:01:05.000
I'm not sure if this labor really is mundane, but the simple fact is that before an R program can look for answers, your data must be cleaned up and converted to a form that makes information accessible.

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:10.000
Learning to do this well is the best investment that you can make in yourself as a data scientist.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:17.000
In these videos, you will learn how to use the dplyr and tidyr packages to optimize the data wrangling process.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:24.000
You'll learn to spot the variables and observations within your data, to quickly derive new variables and observations to explore,

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:35.000
to reshape your data into the layout that works best for R, to join multiple data sets together, and to use group-wise summaries to explore hidden levels of information within your data.

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:43.000
Also, keep in mind that you can skip around these videos to the tool that you want by clicking the jump to links in the video description.

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:53.000
This webinar will go through two packages that Hadley Wickham, my colleague, made, and they're both really geared towards working with the structure of data.

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:56.000
So that's the tidyr package and the dplyr package.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:03.000
And then what I'm going to cover today really follows closely a cheat sheet that we published a couple days ago.

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:07.000
So this is a cheat sheet you can download at the link at the bottom of the slide here.

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:12.000
And it's a two-page sheet that just summarizes the tidyr package and the dplyr package.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:19.000
So it's a great resource for remembering the functions that we're going to go through today, and also for just remembering functions in general as you work with data.

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:29.000
So before we really get into data wrangling, there's a couple of ground rules that I want to familiarize you with.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:35.000
So these two packages introduce some things into R that makes R work better, but also makes R look a little different.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:38.000
So I just want to make sure you're comfortable with that before we start using them.

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:43.000
And the first is the table structure, or tbl, T-B-L.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:50.000
And what a table is, I'm going to say table because I don't like tbl, but it's just a data frame, basically.

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:54.000
You can think of it as a data frame that appears differently in your console window.

00:02:54.000 --> 00:03:02.000
So, for example, if I go over here to my R window, this is just a R studio window that I put off on the side here.

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:06.000
And I open up a familiar library like ggplot2.

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:10.000
There is a data set in here called diamonds, which is humongous.

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:14.000
And if you try to look at this data frame, this is what will happen.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:20.000
It fills up my screen, and at some point R tells me that it's not going to show the rest of the data.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:23.000
This data set is 52,000 rows.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:27.000
And really what I do see here isn't very helpful.

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:32.000
A, it fills up my memory buffer, which means I can't see what I did before.

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:35.000
And B, I can't even see the names of this data frame.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:43.000
So what a table is, is a new class that you can give to a data structure like diamonds.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:51.000
And it's implemented through the dplyr package.

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:56.000
So I can change diamonds into a table with this function table underscore df.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:04.000
And now I have the same data frame here, but the print method is only going to show me the part of the data frame that fits in my console window.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:13.000
So it's showing me right now that there's a variable called y and a variable called z in the diamonds data frame that went off the side of the window.

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:19.000
Instead of wrapping them below, R now is just going to tell me these variables are here, but they're not shown.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:23.000
And then instead of showing me 52,000 rows, it's just going to show me 10 rows.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:28.000
So this is a more pretty way to look at your data.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:39.000
If I were to change my console window to something wider and then look at my table of diamonds, I get those extra variables here.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:44.000
It pays attention to how wide my window is, so it knows how many variables it can show.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:48.000
If I call this again, now it only shows up to depth and so on.

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:53.000
So this is a very useful way to look at large data sets or work with large data sets.

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:57.000
But you, at times, will still want to see your complete data.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:04.000
So there's a function I recommend to use when you want to look at the entire data set, and that's the view function.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:17.000
It's in base R, and if you call it from RStudio, RStudio will open up a spreadsheet-like view window where you can check out your data set, almost as if it were an Excel document.

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:25.000
Keep in mind that's view with a capital V, and you can use this on any data frame that you have in R.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:27.000
Close that.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:32.000
Then there's one last function that really changes how R looks, and that's the pipe operator.

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:36.000
This comes from the Magruder package, but it's imported by the dplyr package.

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:40.000
And it's a different way to write the same code that you'd write before.

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:45.000
So you can probably recognize what this command would do here.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:47.000
We haven't looked at select. We'll look at that today.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:52.000
But it's calling select on an object called tb, and then it has some arguments here.

00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:57.000
The pipe operator allows you to pipe in the first argument of select.

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:00.000
So I'd write tb pipe select child to elderly.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:04.000
And what the operator will do is it will insert tb as the first argument of select.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:07.000
So these two lines of code would do the same thing.

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:11.000
If we come over here, we could take a look at that.

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:14.000
So if I had diamonds, I could pipe in...

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:21.000
Let me just take one variable from diamonds, maybe dx column.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:23.000
And I could pipe that into mean.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:29.000
And if I run this code, it's going to give me the mean of the x column,

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:32.000
which is the same as if I did mean diamonds x.

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:38.000
So at this point, it might not be obvious why you'd use pipe over anything else,

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:44.000
but the cool thing about this format is you can start chaining arguments together.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:50.000
So if I wanted to round every value in the x column of diamonds to the second decimal place,

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:56.000
and then take the mean, I can use this code here, which won't look all that different.

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:01.000
Instead of actually saying like, okay, let's round all this stuff,

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:08.000
round all this stuff, and save that, and then call mean on the output.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:12.000
As your chains get longer and longer, this becomes much more efficient

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:16.000
than actually managing where you save the in-between states.

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:25.000
So let's take a look at the functions that can actually help you wrangle data.

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:29.000
And what I mean by data wrangling is what other people call munging,

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:31.000
or transforming your data, or manipulating it.

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:36.000
And the reason I use the word wrangling is it sort of captures how painful this process can be.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:42.000
That's just getting the format of your data into a format that you can work with is time consuming,

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:44.000
and it's often boring and painful.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:48.000
And if you could do that more efficiently, that would be a big win.

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:51.000
And the functions we'll look at today will help you do that.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:54.000
Thanks for checking out our data wrangling video series.

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:58.000
This is just one video in a larger set of resources on data wrangling.

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:01.000
So here are links to all of our other videos in the series.

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:05.000
And again, have a look at the video description for shortcuts to other parts of the series,

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:10.000
as well as other resources we think might be helpful, like cheat sheets and further documentation.

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:13.000
We hope you find all of these resources useful.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:17.000
And if you do, as always, we would appreciate a thumbs up or a share.

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:21.000
Both go a long way to helping this content reach people who could benefit from it.

